        "body2": "Mark Walsh, whose 19 previous rides at the Cheltenham Festival have failed to yield a single success, will have two more outstanding chances to break his duck at the meeting next week after he was booked to ride Yanworth in Tuesday\u2019s Champion Hurdle and Uxizandre in the Ryanair Chase.\n\nWalsh has multiple Grade One victories to his name in Ireland, including last season\u2019s Irish Gold Cup aboard Carlingford Lough, and has often stepped in for big-race rides in the famous colours of JP McManus when the owner\u2019s No1 jockey has been sidelined by injury or has chosen an alternative mount.\n\nHe is a rare visitor to Britain, however, where Walsh has recorded only three wins from 44 rides, and he has only one success at one of the UK\u2019s two major spring festivals, in a handicap hurdle at Aintree in 2004 when he was a 7lb claimer.\n\nThe rides on Yanworth and Uxizandre became available when Barry Geraghty, McManus\u2019s retained rider, was ruled out of the Festival meeting after suffering three broken ribs and a partially collapsed lung in a fall at Kempton Park nine days ago. Yanworth is currently the narrow 7-2 favourite for the Champion Hurdle, ahead of another McManus-owned runner, Nicky Henderson\u2019s Buveur D\u2019Air, while Uxizandre is 6-1 third-favourite for the Ryanair Chase.\n\n\u201cMark Walsh is going to come over and have a sit on Yanworth and Uxizandre, probably on Thursday, and the plan is that he\u2019ll ride both horses at Cheltenham,\u201d Alan King, who trains both horses, said on Monday.\n\n\u201cI don\u2019t know him at all, but he\u2019s a very good rider. I\u2019ve been very happy with both horses since their last runs and everything has gone well.\u201d\n\nDespite the lack of a past Festival winner against his name, Walsh\u2019s book of rides next week is now so strong he is the 10-1 fourth-favourite to be the meeting\u2019s top rider. His namesake Ruby is the 8-13 favourite to win the award for a 10th time in 