\nThe next tier up is the Gold Edition, which is \u00a384.99 from Game in the UK, or $99.99 from Amazon US, and includes all of the above (except the War Chest is gold), along with two story expansions: The Blade of Galadriel and The Desolation of Mordor. It also comes in a nifty steelbook case.\n\nFinally, for the real die-hards there\u2019s the Mithril Edition, which any LotR fan will know is the best of all the fictional metals. That\u2019s an Amazon exclusive in the UK, and a GameStop exclusive in the US and includes everything in the Gold Edition along with some physical goodies: a magnetic Ring of Power, a cloth map of Mordor, some stickers and lithographs, a soundtrack CD, and the real attraction: a 12in Tar-Goroth Balrog vs. Carnan Drake statue, which does look pretty cool, to be fair. It\u2019ll set you back \u00a3199.99/$299.99.\n\nOh, and if you never played the original Shadow of Mordor, you can grab a Game of the Year copy now for \u00a315/$20.\n\nWhat is the storyline?\n\nThe first announcement trailer for Shadow of War showed off the game\u2019s story, which picks up shortly after the end of Shadow of Mordor, between The Hobbit and The Lord of the Rings, still following Talion and Celebrimbor.\n\nRead next: Best PC games\n\nThey\u2019ve forged a new Ring of Power, and are going behind enemy lines into Mordor to try and spread dissent and undermine Sauron, turning his own army against him. It looks like that will involve fighting a Balrog, the Nazgul, and maybe even Sauron himself along the way - watch the trailer for yourself at the top of the page to see more.\n\nWhat are the gameplay features?\n\nWhile the announcement trailer teased the game\u2019s story, there was little (well, zero) gameplay on display, so we don\u2019t know a lot about what to expect. The press release gives us a little more insight, promising a major expansion to the first game\u2019s innovative Nemesis system, which saw named NPC enemies respond to and pursue the player character across the game.\n\n\u201cThe robust personalization from the first game is now applied to the entire world where the environments and characters are all shaped by player actions and decisions, creating a personal world unique to every gameplay experience,\u201d Warner Bros. claims.\n\nRead next: Best PS4 games\n\nThe new additions include Followers, who \u201cbring about entirely new stories of loyalty, betrayal and revenge,\u201d and Nemesis Fortresses, which \u201callows player to utilize different strategies to conquer dynamic strongholds and create personalized worlds with their unique Orc army.\u201d\n\nThere will be a gameplay reveal on 8 March which will hopefully show us more, and we\u2019ll update this article with all the latest news at that point.", 
        "title": "Watch: Nine new things in Middle-earth: Shadow of War \u2022 Eurogamer.net", 
        "trend": "Shadow of War", 
        "body0": "SAN FRANCISCO\u2014Before I gush about how slick and action-packed Middle Earth: Shadow of War is looking before it comes out for PC and consoles, I'd like to offer a huge warning: I didn't get to play it. Warner Bros. Interactive hosted the Tolkien-universe game's first major demo at a state-of-the-art movie theater down the block from last week's Game Developers Conference. The developers at Monolith carefully hid their controllers behind a theater seat, and the game doesn't come out for almost six months.\n\nFor some incomplete games' previews, those are tolerable limitations, especially if their basic gameplay systems (combat, strategy, interface) are neatly spelled out. And in a few ways, what I saw looks like a \"bigger and better\" Middle Earth: Shadow of Mordor. That isn't a terrible conclusion to draw. (While uneven in some respects, the 2014 action-adventure game enjoyed a solid reception by making the most of its Tolkien license, as opposed to being chained to a single book or film's exact plot.)\n\nBut, in too many other ways, Shadow of War is aiming its swords, axes, arrows, and spectral super-powers a lot higher this time\u2014and doing so in an action-adventure market that is looking quite different than it did in 2014. Thus, my challenge is to piece together how many parts of the demo were withheld for mystery's sake as opposed to being incomplete or bad.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\"You left me to die!\"\n\nThe original game's hero, a ranger named Talion, has returned. His new journey sees him picking up at the moment when Shadow of Mordor (whose spot in the Tolkien timeline lands between the original Hobbit stories and Fellowship of the King) left off. Meaning, Lord of the Rings gaming fans have until August 27 to catch up; any review of the new game will spoil the original.\n\nThe demo revolved around one type of mission that Talion will embark upon multiple times in SoW: infiltrating and conquering a fortified \"nemesis\" outpost. In short, the original game's nemeses, which you typically encountered in normal missions, will now appear in their own giant, enemy-filled buildings. Those structures come in four flavors in the final game, ranging from simpler forts to strongholds, fortresses, and, the biggest ones, citadels. We saw Talion lay waste to a \"level 192\" fort\u2014which, to be clear, wasn't a tiny shack.\n\nBefore each nemesis battle, you'll use menus to examine the strengths and types of enemies you can expect, along with the powers that your own allies will bring into battle. Different creature types favor certain elemental attacks, have more mounts (either cavalry or flying), pester you with more sniper fire, or favor other perks. Monolith insists that enemy variety will be greatly increased\u2014thus responding directly to one of the original game's biggest issues.\n\nBased on how this siege sequence opens, Talion clearly doesn't care for stealth or guerrilla tactics. Each outpost siege begins with your hero marching through a crowd of his allied warriors, all shouting at their intended target. Dialogue plays out between your side and the \"dynamically generated\" enemies, whose traits and powers are supposedly formulated based on your actions throughout the game. Specific shouts about held grudges and desired revenge play out: \"I fought for you, bled for you, and you left me to die!\" shouts a creature named Thrak Storm-Bringer (referring, Monolith said, to another battle you fought in which one of your allies died at your side). \"But I was reborn with the power of the dark lord!\u201d From there, you and your armies charge the fort while enemy arrows rain from above, and Talion starts handing out ass-kickings shortly after he scales one of the fort's rock walls.\n\nMonolith producers insist that much of the dialogue and character design are subject to the game's dynamic-generation whims. \"Thousands and thousands\" of dialogue exchanges have been recorded, Monolith insists, with just as many character designs to match. \"That\u2019s hard for people on our team making content,\" Monolith VP Michael de Plater told Ars. \"That's a lot of awesome character art and dialogue that most people are never going to see or hear.\"\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nWarner Bros. Interactive\n\n\n\n\n\nAt least we get a cool dragon\n\nEverything about the Shadow of War demo looked about as slick as you can imagine. Cinematic flyovers of the fort included grounds and towers covered in orcs, trolls, dragons, and other beasts, all rich in detail and varied in animation and attack patterns. Talion was able to hop onto a dragon, fly around, and smother enemies in burps of flame until the dragon was sacrificed in a dive-bomb attack against an even bigger brute. Each dialogue exchange included the kind of polished-yet-cheesy villain shouts that I expect from a shameless orc bloodbath.\n\nAnd the sequence made sure to show off how my own helper characters could turn the tide at just the right moments. A sniper's carefully aimed arrow went straight into the stabbing arm of a major fort chieftain, just as Talion was about to be sliced to death. Another near-death moment, while battling the fort's primary nemesis, is interrupted by your mount storming in, crashing into the sucker, and sacrificing itself to save your life. Plus, there was a whole crazy thing where a bad guy burnt half of Talion's troops with a giant, burning bath of hot tar, along with, you know, riding that flame-throwing dragon up and over castle walls to even the score.\n\nFurther Reading FTC: Warner Bros. paid YouTubers for positive reviews How much of the demo was perfectly staged to make moments look more dramatic than the actual game will dynamically generate? That's hard to say. What I can speak to is how lacking the demo looked in the compelling-mechanics department. Talion's Arkham-esque melee moves look positively dated in 2017; he can slow time down for automatic, gruesome assassination attacks. But normal battles appear incredibly pedestrian, with no compelling AI or intriguing dodge or attack tweaks. No more than a single enemy attacks at the same time. (Shadow of War does employ quick-time events, however. If you're among the 12 people on the planet who actually want those in your games, you're in luck.)\n\nWorse, Talion's ghost-vision ability to find and target foes has been soundly surpassed by games such as this month's Horizon Zero Dawn. I am compelled to note that Horizon also does a far better job of combining enemy-scans and weak-point data in the heat of battle than Shadow of War's demo appears to do. Monolith only showed most of that data in pre-battle menus, but that could certainly change by the time the game launches.\n\nFurther Reading Middle-earth: Shadow of Mordor: A shadow of its own ambition In terms of cinematic presentation and the whole \"let's be a badass and wipe out an orc fort\" premise, Monolith has clearly put in the legwork to make its battles seem more epic than in the original Mordor game. Perhaps SoW's teased \"fort management\" system will bolster the game's scope, as well. As advertised, these will allow you to receive bonuses based on which types of soldiers you set up in any forts or citadels you overtake. They may get their own \"return and defend\" missions (though that wasn't made entirely clear).\n\nBut we didn't really see how fort management will play out during the rest of the game, let alone a single iota of overworld or open-world mission gameplay. And while \"thousands and thousands\" of revenge-shouting possibilities sound cool, the only hint we got about SoW's mainline campaign is that Monolith admitted the original game's plot was \"too short\" and ended \"too abruptly.\"\n\nde Plater says the game is officially in \"post-alpha\" status, which sets it up for its coming-very-soon launch of August 27. At least we don't have very long to wait for answers to so many questions.\n\nListing image by Warner Bros. Interactive", 
